<p><a name="Notes" id="Notes"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Denis_Diderot&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes</span></h2>
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> Mark Twain, "A Majestic Literary Fossil", originally from <i>Harper's New Monthly Magazine</i>, vol. 80, issue 477, p. 439-444, February 1890. <a href="http://www.harpers.org/AMajesticLiteraryFossil.html" class="external text" title="http://www.harpers.org/AMajesticLiteraryFossil.html" rel="nofollow">Online</a> at <i>Harper's</i> site. Accessed September 24, 2006.</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> Bryan Magee. The Story of Philosophy. DK Publishing, Inc., New York: 1998. page 124</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> Diderot's contemporary, also a Frenchman, Pierre Louis Maupertius <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Louis_Maupertuis" class="external autonumber" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Louis_Maupertuis" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>, who in 1745 was named Head of the Prussian Academy of Science under <a href="/wiki/Frederic_the_Great" title="Frederic the Great" class="mw-redirect">Frederic the Great</a>, was developing similar ideas. These proto-evolutionary theories were by no means as thought out and systematic as those of <a href="/wiki/Darwin" title="Darwin">Darwin</a> a hundred years later.</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> Johnathan I. Israel, <i>Radical Enlightenment: Philosophy and the Making of Modernity 1650-1750.</i> (Oxford University Press. 2001, 2002), p. 710</li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> Denis Diderot as quoted in Lynn Hunt, R. Po-chia Hsia, Thomas R. Martin, Barbara H. Rosenwein, and Bonnie G. Smith, <i>The Making of the West: Peoples and Cultures: A Concise History: Volume II: Since 1340</i>, Second Edition (Boston: Bedford/St. Martin's, 2007), 611.</li>
</ol>
